## Migration to .NET 8 — Cooperative Cancellation

### Pattern Classification

Your code contains:
1. **Cancellable work loop** — `while (_running)` loop
2. **Blocking call interruption** — `GetNextItem()` may block
3. **ThreadAbortException as control flow** — catch does `RollbackCurrentTransaction()`
4. **Thread.ResetAbort** — keeps thread alive after abort

### Why This Breaks on .NET 8

`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` — the runtime no longer supports preemptive thread termination. `ThreadAbortException` is never thrown, so your cleanup logic in the catch block **silently stops running**.

---

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private Thread? _workerThread;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        _workerThread = new Thread(() => ProcessLoop(_cts.Token));
        _workerThread.IsBackground = true;
        _workerThread.Start();
    }

    private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            bool itemStarted = false;
            try
            {
                var item = GetNextItem(token); // pass token to unblock
                itemStarted = true;
                ProcessItem(item, token);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Cancellation requested — roll back any partial work
                if (itemStarted)
                    RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                break; // exit the loop
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        if (_cts is null) return;

        _cts.Cancel(); // signal cooperative cancellation

        // Give thread time to finish gracefully
        _workerThread?.Join(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2));
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts?.Dispose();
    }
}
```

### What Changed and Why

| Original | Migrated | Reason |
|----------|----------|--------|
| `volatile bool _running` | `CancellationToken` | Token integrates with blocking APIs; a bool cannot wake a blocked thread |
| `Thread.Abort()` | `_cts.Cancel()` | Cooperative signal — no `PlatformNotSupportedException` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` | This is what `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` and cancellation-aware APIs throw |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Removed | Not needed — you control whether to `break` or continue |
| `Thread.Sleep(2000)` | `_workerThread.Join(2s)` | Actually waits for thread exit instead of hoping |

---

### Critical: Update `GetNextItem` to Accept a Token

The original code says `GetNextItem()` "may block." If it blocks indefinitely, cancellation **never takes effect** because cooperative cancellation only works at checkpoints. You **must** make blocking calls cancellation-aware:

```csharp
// If using a BlockingCollection<T>:
private WorkItem GetNextItem(CancellationToken token)
{
    return _queue.Take(token); // throws OperationCanceledException on cancel
}

// If using a custom wait:
private WorkItem GetNextItem(CancellationToken token)
{
    while (!_itemAvailable.WaitOne(500))
    {
        token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();
    }
    return DequeueItem();
}
```

---

### Key Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Impact |
|---------|--------|
| **Not passing token to `GetNextItem`** | Thread stays blocked forever after `Cancel()` — your `Stop()` never returns |
| **Catching `OperationCanceledException` and swallowing it** | Let it propagate or explicitly `break` — don't accidentally continue the loop |
| **Forgetting to dispose `CancellationTokenSource`** | Leaks internal timers and registered callbacks |
| **Assuming cancellation is instant** | It only fires at the next checkpoint; if `ProcessItem` runs for 30s without checking, you wait 30s |
| **Removing rollback logic when deleting the catch block** | The old `ThreadAbortException` catch contained `RollbackCurrentTransaction()` — this cleanup must survive the migration |
